    <statement><p>Simplify this expression, and if applicable, write the restricted domain.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\frac{{\frac{9p+1}{p}}}{{\frac{p-8}{p}}}}</m> = <fillin characters="40" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\frac{9p+1}{p-8}, p\ne 0</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To simply the complex fraction <m>\frac{{\frac{9p+1}{p}}}{{\frac{p-8}{p}}}</m>, we multiple the numerator and denominator with the common denominator of <m>{\frac{9p+1}{p}}</m> and <m>{\frac{p-8}{p}}</m>, which is <m>{p}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
  \frac{{\frac{9p+1}{p}}}{{\frac{p-8}{p}}} \amp = \frac{{\frac{9p+1}{p}}\cdot{p}}{{\frac{p-8}{p}}\cdot{p}} \\
    \amp = {\frac{9p+1}{p-8}, p\ne 0}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Since <m>{p}</m> was canceled, <m>p \ne 0</m> is in a lost domain condition.</p>
</solution>
